ges=|url=https://archive.org/details/raisingkanyelive00west|accessdate=}}\n\n== External links ==\n* ''[http://www.discogs.com/Kanye-West-The-College-Dropout/master/6983 The College Dropout]'' at [[Discogs]]\n\n{{Kanye West}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for ''The College Dropout''\n| titlestyle = background: lightblue\n| list1 =\n{{Grammy Award for Best Rap Album}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:College Dropout, The}}\n[[Category:2004 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Kanye West]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings albums]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Rap Album]]\n[[Category:Kanye West albums]]\n[[Category:Pop-rap albums]]\n[[Category:Roc-A-Fella Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the article on dropping out of college|Dropping out}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The College Dropout\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Kanye West]]\n| cover      = Kanyewest collegedropout.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2004|02|10}}\n| recorded   = 1999\u20132003\n| venue      =\n| studio     = \n* Baseline, Full Time Dreamer, Light @ the End of the Tunnel, Quad, and [[Sony Music Studios|Sony Music]] (New York City, New York)\n* [[Conway Recording Studios|Conway]] and [[Larrabee Sound Studios|Larrabee Sound North]] (Los Angeles, California)\n* Digital Insight (Las Vegas, Nevada)\n* Edie Road ([[Argyle, New York]])\n* The Enterprise ([[Burbank, California]])\n* [[Record Plant]] (Hollywood, California)\n| genre      = \n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[chipmunk soul]]\n* [[conscious rap]]\n* [[pop rap]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=76|s=13}}\n| label      = \n* [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n* [[Roc-A-Fella Records|Roc-A-Fella]]\n| producer   = Kanye West\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Late Registration]]\n| next_year  = 2005\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The College Dropout\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Through the Wire]]\n | single1date = September 30, 2003\n | single2     = [[Slow Jamz]]\n | single2date = December 2, 2003\n | single3     = [[All Falls Down]]\n | single3date = February 24, 2004\n | single4     = [[Jesus Walks]]\n | single4date = May 25, 2004\n | single5     = [[The New Workout Plan]]\n | single5date = August 31, 2004\n}}\n}}\n'''''The College Dropout''''' is the debut studio album by American rapper and producer [[Kanye West]]. It was released on February 10, 2004, by [[Def Jam Recordings]] and [[Roc-A-Fella Records]]. In the years leading up to release, West had received praise for his production work for rappers such as [[Jay-Z]] and [[Talib Kweli]], but faced difficulty being accepted as an artist in his own right by figures in the [[music industry]]. Intent on pursuing a solo career, he signed a record deal with Roc-A-Fella and recorded the album over a period of four years, beginning in 1999.\n\nThe production of ''The College Dropout'' was primarily handled by West and developed his \"chipmunk soul\" production style, which made use of sped-up, [[pitch shift]]ed vocal [[Sampling (music)|samples]] from [[soul music|soul]] and [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] records, in addition to West's own [[drum machine|drum programming]], string accompaniments, and [[Gospel music|gospel choir]]s; the album also features contributions from Jay-Z, [[Mos Def]], [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Syleena Johnson]], and [[Ludacris]], among others. Diverging from the then-dominant [[Gangsta rap|gangster persona]] in hip hop, West's lyrics concern themes of family, [[self-consciousness]], [[economic materialism|materialism]], religion, racism, and higher education.\n\n''The College Dropout'' debuted at number two on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 441,000 copies in its first week of sales. It was a large-scale commercial success, becoming West's best-selling album in the United States, with domestic sales of over 3.4&nbsp;million copies by 2014 and was certified triple platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) the next year. The album was promoted with singles such as \"[[Through the Wire]]\", \"[[Jesus Walks]]\", \"[[All Falls Down]]\", and \"[[Slow Jamz]]\", the latter two of which peaked within the top ten of the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\nA widespread critical success, ''The College Dropout'' was praised for West's production, humorous and emotional raps, and the music's balance of self-examination and mainstream sensibilities. The album earned the rapper several accolades including a [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Album]] at the [[47th Annual Grammy Awards|2005 Grammy Awards]]. It has since been named by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', and other publications as one of the greatest albums of all time and credited for popularizing the [[chipmunk soul]] and [[conscious rap]] subgenres in the 2000s.\n\n== Background ==\nKanye West began his early production career in the mid-1990s, making beats primarily for burgeoning local artists, eventually developing a style that involved speeding up vocal samples from classic soul records. For a time, he acted as a ghost producer for Deric \"D-Dot\" Angelettie. Due to his association with D-Dot, West wasn't able to release a solo album, so he formed and became a member and producer of the Go-Getters, a late-1990s Chicago rap group composed of him, [[GLC (rapper)|GLC]], Timmy G, [[Really Doe]], and Arrowstar.<ref name=Barber>{{cite web|author=Barber, Andrew|title=93. Go-Getters \"Let Em In\" (2000)|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/the-100-best-kanye-west-songs/let-em-in|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|publisher=Complex Media|date=July 23, 2012|accessdate=August 7, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727014600/http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/the-100-best-kanye-west-songs/let-em-in|archive-date=July 27, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Reid, Shaheem |title=Music Geek Kanye's Kast of Thousands |url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/m/music_geek/kanyewest_100305/ |work=MTV |publisher=MTV Networks |date=September 30, 2005 |accessdate=April 23, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060415173601/http://www.mtv.com/bands/m/music_geek/kanyewest_100305/ |archive-date=April 15, 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref> The group released their first and only studio album ''World Record Holders'' in 1999.<ref name=Barber/> West came to achieve recognition with his contributions to Jay-Z's influential 2001 album ''[[The Blueprint]]''.<ref name=\"Mitchum\"/> ''The Blueprint'' has been named by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' as the 252nd greatest album of all time and the critical and financial success of the album generated substantial interest in West as a producer.<ref name=\"RS500\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/jay-z-the-blueprint-20120524|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time: #464 (The Blueprint)|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner]]|date=November 18, 2003|accessdate=June 21, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022141153/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/jay-z-the-blueprint-20120524|archive-date=October 22, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Serving as an in-house producer for Roc-A-Fella Records, West produced records for other artists from the label, including [[Beanie Sigel]], [[Freeway (rapper)|Freeway]], and [[Cam'ron]]. He also crafted hit songs for [[Ludacris]], [[Alicia Keys]], and [[Janet Jackson]].<ref name=\"Mitchum\"/><ref name=\"Kellman\"/><ref name=Road/><ref name=auto>Serpick, Evan. [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/kanye-west/biography Kanye West] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111216151530/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/kanye-west/biography |date=December 16, 2011 }}. ''Rolling Stone'' Jann Wenner. Retrieved on December 26, 2009.</ref>\n\nAlthough he had attained success as a producer, Kanye West aspired to be a rapper, but had struggled to attain a record deal.<ref name=Road/> Record companies ignored him because he did not portray the gangsta image prominent in mainstream hip hop at the time.<ref name=Hess-p556>Hess, p. 556</ref> After a series of meetings with [[Capitol Records]], West was ultimately denied an artist deal.<ref name=KanplicatedPg2>{{cite web | author=Calloway, Sway | author2=Reid, Shaheem | title=Kanye West: Kanplicated | url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/w/west_kanye/news_feature_022404/index2.jhtml | date=February 20, 2004 | work=MTV | publisher=MTV Networks | accessdate=April 21, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406021640/http://www.mtv.com/bands/w/west_kanye/news_feature_022404/index2.jhtml | archivedate=April 6, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> According to Capitol Record's A&R, Joe Weinberger, he was approached by West and almost signed a deal with him, but another person in the company convinced Capitol's president not to.<ref name=KanplicatedPg2/> Desperate to keep West from defecting to another label, then-label head [[Damon Dash]] reluctantly signed West to [[Roc-A-Fella Records]]. [[Jay-Z]], West's colleague, later admitted that Roc-A-Fella was initially reluctant to support West as a rapper, claiming that many saw him as a producer first and foremost, and that his background contrasted with that of his labelmates.<ref name=Hess-p556/><ref>{{cite web|author=Williams, Jean A|accessdate=April 27, 2008|url=http://www.blackcollegian.com/kanye-west-the-man-the-music-and-the-message/|title=Kanye West: The Man, the Music, and the Message.(Biography)|publisher=The Black Collegian|date=October 1, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150125003250/http://www.blackcollegian.com/kanye-west-the-man-the-music-and-the-message/|archivedate=January 25, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nWest's breakthrough came a year later on October 23, 2002, when, while driving home from a California recording studio after working late, he fell asleep at the wheel and was involved in a near-fatal car crash.<ref name=wsws/> The crash left him with a shattered jaw, which had to be wired shut in reconstructive surgery. The accident inspired West; two weeks after being admitted to a hospital, he recorded a song at the [[Record Plant]] with his jaw still wired shut.<ref name=wsws/> The composition, \"[[Through the Wire]]\", expressed West's experience after the accident, and helped lay the foundation for his debut album, as according to West \"all the better artists have expressed what they were going through\".<ref name=\"amg\">{{cite web|year=2007|accessdate=April 24, 2008|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p353484|pure_url=yes}}|title=Kanye West \u2013 Biography|last=Birchmeier|first=Jason|publisher=AllMusic. All Media Guide}}</ref><ref name=ebony/> West added that \"the album was my medicine\", as working on the record distracted him from the pain.<ref>Davis, Kimberly. [https://books.google.com/books?id=EFWfRrCKBCIC&pg=PA160 \"Kanye West: Hip Hop's New Big Shot\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106210658/https://books.google.com/books?id=EFWfRrCKBCIC&pg=PA160 |date=January 6, 2016 }} (April 2005) ''[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]''.</ref> \"Through the Wire\" was first available on West's ''Get Well Soon...'' [[mixtape]], released December 2002.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kamer, Foster|accessdate=April 9, 2013|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/03/the-50-best-rapper-mixtapes/kanye-west-get-well-soon|title=9. Kanye West, Get Well Soon... (2003) \u2013 The 50 Best Rapper Mixtapes|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=March 11, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313223732/http://www.complex.com/music/2013/03/the-50-best-rapper-mixtapes/kanye-west-get-well-soon|archivedate=March 13, 2013}}</ref> At the same time, West announced that he was working on an album called ''The College Dropout'', whose overall theme was to \"make your own decisions. Don't let society tell you, 'This is what you have to do.'\"<ref>Reid, Shaheem (December 10, 2002). \"[http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1459071/kanye-west-raps-through-broken-jaw.jhtml Kanye West Raps Through His Broken Jaw, Lays Beats For Scarface, Ludacris] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228152622/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1459071/kanye-west-raps-through-broken-jaw.jhtml |date=December 28, 2013 }}\". MTV. Accessed October 23, 2007.</ref>\n\n== Recording ==\n[[File:West performing.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Kanye West in 2007.|West (center) refined the album's production and incorporated elements such as gospel choirs and string arrangements.]]\nWest began recording ''The College Dropout'' in 1999, taking four years to complete.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sarad|date=February 10, 2015|url=http://thesource.com/2015/02/10/today-in-hip-hop-history-kanye-west-drops-his-college-dropout-lp-11-years-ago/|title=Today in Hip Hop History: Kanye West Drops His 'College Dropout' LP 11 Years Ago|website=[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]|accessdate=January 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121118/http://thesource.com/2015/02/10/today-in-hip-hop-history-kanye-west-drops-his-college-dropout-lp-11-years-ago/|archive-date=January 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Recording sessions took place at [[Record Plant]] in Los Angeles, California, but the production featured on the record took place elsewhere over the course of several years. According to John Monopoly, West's friend, manager and business partner, the album \"...[didn't have] a particular start date. He's been gathering beats for years. He was always producing with the intention of being a rapper. There's beats on the album he's been literally saving for himself for years\". At one point, West hovered between making a portion of the production in the studio and the majority within his own apartment in [[Newark, New Jersey]]. Because it was a two-bedroom apartment, West was able to set up a home studio in one of the rooms and his bedroom in the other.<ref name=Road/>\n\nWest brought with him to the studio a [[Louis Vuitton]] backpack filled with old disks and demos to the studio, producing tracks in less than fifteen minutes at a time. He recorded the remainder of the album in Los Angeles while recovering from the car accident. Once he had completed the album, it was leaked months before its release date.<ref name=Road/> However, West decided to use the opportunity to review the album, and ''The College Dropout'' was significantly remixed, remastered, and revised before being released. As a result, certain tracks originally destined for the album were subsequently retracted, among them \"Keep the Receipt\" with [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]] and \"The Good, the Bad, and the Ugly\" with Consequence.<ref>{{cite web | last=Patel | first=Joseph | title=Producer Kanye West's Debut LP Features Jay-Z, ODB, Mos Def | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1472302/kanye-west-readying-debut-lp.jhtml | date=June 5, 2003 | work=MTV | publisher=MTV Networks | accessdate=April 21, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026080735/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1472302/kanye-west-readying-debut-lp.jhtml | archivedate=October 26, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> West meticulously refined the production, adding [[String section|string arrangements]], [[Gospel music|gospel choir]]s, improved drum programming and new verses.<ref name=Road>{{Cite news |last=Reid |first=Shaheem |title=Road to the Grammys: The Making Of Kanye West's College Dropout |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1496766/road-grammys-kanye-west.jhtml |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=February 9, 2005 |accessdate=January 4, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718104107/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1496766/road-grammys-kanye-west.jhtml |archivedate=July 18, 2011  }}</ref> On his personal blog in 2009, West stated he was most inspired by ''[[The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill]]'' and listened to the album everyday while working on ''The College Dropout''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Dy1kJrpWkAAG3K_.jpg |title=The College Dropout is EW's Top Album of the Decade |publisher=KanyeUniverseCity |date=December 7, 2009 |accessdate=February 8, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208094103/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Dy1kJrpWkAAG3K_.jpg |archivedate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe song \"School Spirit\" was censored for the album because [[Aretha Franklin]] would not allow the rapper to sample her music without censorship being promised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2013/02/when-rap-lyrics-get-censored-even-on-the-explicit-version/|title=When Rap Lyrics Get Censored, Even on the Explicit Version|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|access-date=September 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913150458/https://www.complex.com/music/2013/02/when-rap-lyrics-get-censored-even-on-the-explicit-version/|archive-date=September 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It was revealed by [[Plain Pat]] that there were around three other versions of the song, but West disliked them. Pat said in reference to the Franklin sample: \"That song would have been so weak if we didn't get that sample cleared\".<ref name=\"making\">{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2014/02/kanye-west-college-dropout-making-of/|title=The Making of Kanye West's \"The College Dropout\"|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|access-date=September 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913150518/https://www.complex.com/music/2014/02/kanye-west-college-dropout-making-of/|archive-date=September 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2011, an uncensored version of the track was distributed online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fakeshoredrive.com/2011/05/kanye-west-school-spirit-uncensored-version.html/|title=Kanye West \u2013 School Spirit (Uncensored Version)|work=Fake Shore Drive\u00ae|access-date=July 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730025242/https://www.fakeshoredrive.com/2011/05/kanye-west-school-spirit-uncensored-version.html/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWest finished recording around December 2003, according to his older cousin and singer [[The World Famous Tony Williams|Tony Williams]], who was recruited by the rapper two weeks before the album's deadline to contribute vocals. Williams had impressed West by singing improvisations to \"[[Spaceship (Kanye West song)|Spaceship]]\" during one of their drives together. The singer later recounted recording with West at the Record Plant: \"I get in, go in the booth, start vibing out on 'Spaceship' and finished it up. At that point he was like, 'Ok, Well let me see what you do on this song.' I think that's when we did 'Last Call.' One song lead to another, and by the end of the weekend, I was on like five songs. Then we did the 'I'll Fly Away' join\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Martins|first=Jordan|date=April 19, 2010|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2010/04/tony-williams-of-g-o-o-d-music-talks-most-memorable-studio-sessions-with-kanye|title=Tony Williams of G.O.O.D. Music Talks Most Memorable Studio Sessions With Kanye|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=January 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728002927/https://www.complex.com/music/2010/04/tony-williams-of-g-o-o-d-music-talks-most-memorable-studio-sessions-with-kanye|archive-date=July 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n''The College Dropout'' diverged from the then-dominant [[gangsta rap|gangster persona]] in hip hop in favor of more diverse, topical subjects for the lyrics.<ref name=ebony>Davis, Kimberly. [https://books.google.com/books?id=J9kDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA93 \"The Many Faces of Kanye West\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106210658/https://books.google.com/books?id=J9kDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA93 |date=January 6, 2016 }} (June 2004) ''[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]''.</ref> Throughout the album, West touches on a number of different issues drawn from his own experiences and observations, including organized religion, family, sexuality, excessive materialism, self-consciousness, [[minimum wage]] labor, [[Institutional racism|institutional prejudice]], and personal struggles.<ref name=\"Love\">Love, Josh. [http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/kanye-west/the-college-dropout.htm Review: ''The College Dropout''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060915033648/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/kanye-west/the-college-dropout.htm |date=September 15, 2006 }}. [[Stylus Magazine]]. Retrieved on July 23, 2009.</ref><ref name=\"Cinquemani\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/article/2009912270315 |title=Music of the decade |date=December 27, 2009 |last=James |first=Jim |newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]] |archiveurl=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/1928558221.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+27%2C+2009&author=&pub=Courier+-+Journal&edition=&startpage=I.3&desc=Music+of+the+decade |archivedate=June 17, 2011 |accessdate=June 17, 2011}}</ref> Music journalist [[Kelefa Sanneh]] wrote, \"Throughout the album, Mr. West taunts everyone who didn't believe in him: teachers, record executives, police officers, even his former boss at the [[Gap Inc.|Gap]]\".<ref name=\"Sanneh\"/> West explained, \"My persona is that I'm the regular person. Just think about whatever you've been through in the past week, and I have a song about that on my album\".<ref>{{cite web| title=Kanye West Biography| url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/music/artist/bio/0,,721308,00.html| work=[[Artistdirect]]| publisher=Rogue Digital, LLC.| accessdate=August 7, 2012| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418070657/http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/music/artist/bio/0%2C%2C721308%2C00.html| archivedate=April 18, 2012| df=mdy-all}}</ref> The album was musically notable for West's unique development of his \"chipmunk soul\" production style,<ref>[http://www.unrecorded.mu/features/flashbacks/flashback-kanye-west-the-college-dropout/ Unrecorded] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201094744/http://www.unrecorded.mu/features/flashbacks/flashback-kanye-west-the-college-dropout/ |date=February 1, 2014 }}</ref> in which [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] and [[soul music]] [[Sampling (music)|samples]] were sped up and [[pitch shift]]ed.<ref>[http://sabotagetimes.com/music/history-in-the-making-man-how-the-college-dropout-changed-hip-hop-forever ''Sabotage Times''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224135022/http://sabotagetimes.com/music/history-in-the-making-man-how-the-college-dropout-changed-hip-hop-forever |date=February 24, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"king\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/kanye-west-king-of-rap-403127.html|title=Kanye West: King of rap|work=[[The Independent]]|location=UK |date=September 22, 2007|accessdate=April 26, 2008|author=Burrell, Ian }}</ref>\n\n{{Listen\n| pos = right\n| filename = Throughthewire.ogg\n| title = \"Through the Wire\"\n| description = \"[[Through the Wire]]\" is an autobiographical song about West's 2002 car accident when he had to have his jaw wired shut. The track is representative of his production style, in which he [[Sampling (music)|samples]] and speeds up sections from classic [[Soul music|soul]] records and uses them to create melodic [[Hook (music)|hooks]].\n| format = [[Ogg]]\n| filename2    = \n| title2       = \"Jesus Walks\"\n| description2 = \"[[Jesus Walks]]\" has a gospel-influenced sound, with a pulsing rhythm reminiscent of a [[marching band]] accompanied by [[baritone]] background vocal samples from the ARC Choir's arrangement of the traditional gospel song \"Walk With Me\".\n| format2 = Ogg\n}}\nThe album begins with a [[Hip hop skit|skit]] featuring a college professor asking West to deliver a graduation speech. The skit is followed by \"We Don't Care\" featuring West comically celebrating drug life with lines like \"We wasn't supposed to make it past 25, joke's on you, we still alive\" and then criticizing its influence amongst children.<ref name=\"Sanneh\"/> The next track, \"Graduation Day\", features [[Miri Ben-Ari]] on violin,<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/61742/hip-hop-violinist-preps-solo-debut 'Hip-Hop Violinist' Preps Solo Debut] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602165343/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/61742/hip-hop-violinist-preps-solo-debut |date=June 2, 2013 }}, ''Billboard''.</ref> and vocals by [[John Legend]].<ref name=linernotes/>\n\nOn \"[[All Falls Down]]\", West wages an attack on consumerism.<ref name=\"Kellman\"/><ref name=\"Heaton\">Heaton, Dave (March 5, 2004). [http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/westkanye-college Kanye West: The College Dropout] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811153127/http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/westkanye-college/ |date=August 11, 2011 }}. ''[[PopMatters]]''. Retrieved on August 25, 2011</ref> The song features singer Syleena Johnson and contains an [[Interpolation (music)|interpolation]] of [[Lauryn Hill]]'s \"Mystery of Iniquity\".<ref name=linernotes/> West called upon Johnson to re-sing a vocal portion of \"Mystery of Iniquity\", which ended up in the final mix.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hall |first=Rashaun |title=Kanye West Collaborating With Lauryn Hill on New LP |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1496152/kanye-collaborating-with-lauryn-hill.jhtml |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=January 21, 2005 |accessdate=January 4, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107050940/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1496152/kanye-collaborating-with-lauryn-hill.jhtml |archivedate=January 7, 2011  }}</ref> Gospel hymn with [[doo-wop]] elements \"[[I'll Fly Away]]\" precedes \"Spaceship\", a track with a relaxed beat containing a soulful [[Marvin Gaye]] sample. The lyrics are mostly critical of the working world, where West muses about flying away in a spaceship to leave his boring job, and guest rappers [[GLC (rapper)|GLC]] and [[Consequence (rapper)|Consequence]] add comparisons to modern day retail environment with slavery.<ref name=\"Heaton\"/>\n\nOn \"[[Jesus Walks]]\", West professes his belief in Jesus, while also discussing how religion is used by various people and how the media seems to avoid songs that address matters of faith while embracing compositions on violence, sex, and drugs.<ref name=\"Heaton\"/><ref name=USAToday>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Steve |title=Kanye West runs away with 'Jesus Walks' |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2005-02-10-kanye-west-main_x.htm |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=February 10, 2005 |accessdate=January 7, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025231046/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2005-02-10-kanye-west-main_x.htm |archive-date=October 25, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"Jesus Walks\" is built around a sample of \"Walk With Me\" as performed by the ARC Choir.<ref name=linernotes/> Garry Mulholland of ''[[The Observer]]'' described it as a \"towering inferno of martial beats, fathoms-deep [[chain gang]] backing chants, a defiant children's [[choir]], [[Gospel music|gospel]] wails, and sizzling orchestral breaks\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Mulholland |first=Garry |title='Jesus Walks' by Kanye West |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/omm/reviews/story/0,,1280189,00.html#article_continue |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |date=August 15, 2004 |accessdate=January 7, 2009 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819121545/http://observer.guardian.co.uk/omm/reviews/story/0%2C%2C1280189%2C00.html#article_continue |archivedate=August 19, 2007  }}</ref> The first verse of the song is told through the eyes of a drug dealer seeking help from God, and it reportedly took over six months for West to draw inspiration for the second verse.<ref name=KanplicatedPg3>{{cite web | author=Calloway, Sway | author2=Reid, Shaheem | title=Kanye West: Kanplicated | url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/w/west_kanye/news_feature_022404/index3.jhtml | date=February 20, 2004 | work=MTV | publisher=MTV Networks | accessdate=April 21, 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406032044/http://www.mtv.com/bands/w/west_kanye/news_feature_022404/index3.jhtml | archivedate=April 6, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n\"[[Never Let Me Down (Kanye West song)|Never Let Me Down]]\" is influenced by West's near-death car crash. The song features Jay-Z, who rhymes about maintaining status and power given his chart success, while West comments on racism and poverty.<ref name=\"Heaton\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/468192/watch-the-throne-jay-z-and-kanye-wests-10-best-collaborations?page=0%2C1|title='Watch The Throne': Jay-Z and Kanye West's 10 Best Collaborations|date=August 6, 2011|accessdate=April 3, 2013|work=Billboard|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602184310/http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/468192/watch-the-throne-jay-z-and-kanye-wests-10-best-collaborations?page=0%2C1|archivedate=June 2, 2013}}</ref> The song features verses by spoken word performer [[J. Ivy]] who offers comments of upliftment. \"Never Let Me Down\" reuses a Jay-Z verse first heard in the remix of his song \"[[Hovi Baby]]\".<ref name=\"Heaton\"/><ref name=\"Batey\">Batey, Angus (February 20, 2004). [https://web.archive.org/web/20070319042251/http://uk.launch.yahoo.com/040220/33/1wazr.html Kanye West \u2013 The College Dropout]. ''[[Yahoo! Music]]''. Retrieved on August 25, 2011</ref> \"Get Em High\" is a collaboration by West with two socially conscious rappers, [[Talib Kweli]] and [[Common (rapper)|Common]].<ref name=\"common\"/> \"[[The New Workout Plan]]\" is a call to fitness to improve one's love life.<ref name=\"Heaton\"/> \"[[Slow Jamz]]\" features [[Twista]] and [[Jamie Foxx]] and serves as a tribute to classic [[smooth soul]] artists and [[slow jam]] songs.<ref name=\"Kellman\"/> The song also appeared on Twista's album ''[[Kamikaze (Twista album)|Kamikaze]]''.<ref name=\"Kellman\"/> On the song \"School Spirit\", West relates the experience of dropping out of school and contains references to well-known [[Fraternity|fraternities]], [[Fraternities and sororities|sororities]], singer [[Norah Jones]], and record label Roc-A-Fella Records. \"[[Two Words]]\" features commentary on social issues and features [[Mos Def]], Freeway, and the Harlem Boys Choir.<ref name=\"Ryan\">Ryan, Chris. [http://www.spin.com/reviews/kanye-west-college-dropout-roc-fella Review: ''The College Dropout''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115171907/http://spin.com/reviews/kanye-west-college-dropout-roc-fella |date=January 15, 2010 }}. ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''. Retrieved on December 26, 2009.</ref>\n\n\"Through the Wire\" features a high-pitched vocal sample of [[Chaka Khan]] and relates West's real life experience with being in a car accident.<ref name=wsws/> The song provides a mostly comedic account of his difficult recovery, and features West rapping with his jaw still wired shut from the accident.<ref name=wsws>Kearney, Kevin (September 30, 2005). [http://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2005/09/kany-s30.html Rapper Kanye West on the cover of Time: Will rap music shed its \"gangster\" disguise?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224175108/https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2005/09/kany-s30.html |date=February 24, 2016 }}. World Socialist Web Site. Retrieved September 23, 2007.</ref><ref name=linernotes/> The [[refrain|chorus]] and [[instrumental]]s sample a pitched up version of Chaka Khan's 1985 single \"[[Through the Fire (song)|Through the Fire]]\".<ref name=Kellman/> \"Family Business\" is a soulful tribute to the godbrother of Tarrey Torae, one of the many collaborators in the album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ahmed|first1=Isanul|title=15 Things You Didn't Know About Kanye West's \"The College Dropout\"|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/02/kanye-west-college-dropout-things-you-didnt-know/|website=complex.com|publisher=Complex|accessdate=February 8, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208231025/http://www.complex.com/music/2014/02/kanye-west-college-dropout-things-you-didnt-know/|archivedate=February 8, 2015}}</ref> The song \"Last Call\" is about West's transition from being a producer to a rapper, and the album ends with a nearly nine-minute autobiographical monologue that follows the song \"Last Call\", however, is not a separate track.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barber|first=Andrew|title=The 100 Best Kanye West Songs: 24. Kanye West \"Last Call\" (2004)|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/the-100-best-kanye-west-songs/last-call|work=Complex Music|publisher=Complex Media|accessdate=January 25, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140630005419/http://www.complex.com/music/2012/07/the-100-best-kanye-west-songs/last-call|archivedate=June 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Title and packaging ==\n[[File:Kanye West Dropout Bear Graffiti.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Graffiti that depicts Dropout Bear, the anthropomorphic [[teddy bear]] mascot of [[Kanye West]] that is located in the [[The Bronx|Bronx]], [[New York City]].|Graffiti depicting the Dropout Bear.]]\nThe album's title is in part a reference to West's decision to drop out of college to pursue his dream of becoming a musician.<ref>West, Donda, p. 106</ref> This action greatly displeased his mother, who was a professor at the university from which he withdrew. She later said, \"It was drummed into my head that college is the ticket to a good life... but some career goals don't require college. For Kanye to make an album called ''College Dropout'' it was more about having the guts to embrace who you are, rather than following the path society has carved out for you\".<ref name=Hess-p558>Hess, p. 558</ref>\n\nThe artwork for the album was developed by Eric Duvauchelle, who was then part of Roc-A-Fella's in-house brand design team. West had already taken pictures dressed as the Dropout Bear - which would reappear in his later work - and Duvauchelle picked the image of him sitting on a set of [[bleacher]]s, as he was attracted to the loneliness of what was supposed to be \"the most popular representation of a school\". The image is framed inside gold ornaments, which Duvauchelle found in a book of illustrations from the 16th-century and West wanted to use to \"bring a sense of elegance and style to what was typically a [[gangsta rap|gangster-led image of rap artists]]\". The inside cover follows a college [[yearbook]], with photos of the featured artists of the albums from their youth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/art-design/2013/06/the-design-evolution-of-kanye-wests-album-artwork/the-college-dropout|title=The Design Evolution of Kanye West's Album Artwork: ''The College Dropout''|author1=Pasori, Cedar|author2=McDonald, Leighton|date=June 17, 2013|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=August 7, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621203335/http://www.complex.com/art-design/2013/06/the-design-evolution-of-kanye-wests-album-artwork/the-college-dropout|archivedate=June 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Marketing and sales ==\n''The College Dropout'' was originally scheduled for release in August 2003, but West's perfectionist habits producing the album led to it being postponed three times. It was first delayed to October 2003, then to January 2004, before finally being released to stores on February 10, 2004.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/westkanye-getwellsoon/|title=Kanye West: Get Well Soon / I'm Good|first=Hartley|last=Goldstein|date=December 5, 2003|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=March 21, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227103009/http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/westkanye-getwellsoon/|archivedate=February 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.best.complex.com/music/2011/09/clinton-sparks-30-favorite-mixtapes/get-well-soon |title=Kanye West \u00d7 The Heavy Hitters, Get Well Soon (2003) \u2013 Clinton Sparks' 30 Favorite Mixtapes |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=September 21, 2011 |accessdate=December 9, 2012 |author=Ahmed, Insanul |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130119184429/http://cdn.best.complex.com/music/2011/09/clinton-sparks-30-favorite-mixtapes/get-well-soon |archivedate=January 19, 2013 }}</ref> \n\nIn its first week of release, the album sold 441,000 copies and debuted at number two on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, being held off the top spot by [[Norah Jones]]' second studio album ''[[Feels Like Home (Norah Jones album)|Feels Like Home]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1444628/jones-tops-chart-with-huge-opening-week|title=More Than A Million Take Norah 'Home'|last=Martens|first=Todd|date=February 18, 2004|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=February 17, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522174953/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1444628/jones-tops-chart-with-huge-opening-week|archivedate=May 22, 2013}}</ref> ''The College Dropout'' remained at the second spot behind ''Feels Like Home'' for two consecutive weeks, with 196,000 units sold in the second week and 132,000 in the third week, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1443945/norah-still-tops-on-billboard-200|title=Jones Remains At 'Home' At No. 1|last=Martens|first=Todd|date=February 25, 2004|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=February 17, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604120312/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1443945/norah-still-tops-on-billboard-200|archivedate=June 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1443277/jones-maintains-chart-grip|title=Norah Makes Comfy 'Home' At No. 1|last=Martens|first=Todd|date=March 3, 2004|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=February 17, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602185849/http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1443277/jones-maintains-chart-grip|archivedate=June 2, 2013}}</ref> In 2004, ''The College Dropout'' ranked as the twelfth most popular of the year on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name=\"Billboard 200\"/> The album had sold 2.3 million units in the United States by November 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/66011/kanye-inks-deal-for-sony-label|title=Kanye Inks Deal For Sony Label|website=Billboard|date=October 20, 2004|accessdate=February 20, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141003134053/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/66011/kanye-inks-deal-for-sony-label|archivedate=October 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> By June 2014, the album had become West's best-selling album in the US, with domestic sales of 3,358,000 copies.<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{cite web | url=https://ca.music.yahoo.com/photos/top-new-acts-since-2000-1403561474-slideshow/bonnaroo-2014-photo-1402957045872.html | title=USA: Top 20 New Acts Since 2000 | publisher=Yahoo! Music | date=June 24, 2014 | last=Grein | first=Paul | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714145809/https://ca.music.yahoo.com/photos/top-new-acts-since-2000-1403561474-slideshow/bonnaroo-2014-photo-1402957045872.html | archivedate=July 14, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Cibola, Marco|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/1566931/kanye-west-how-the-rapper-grew-from-dropout-to-yeezus|title=Kanye West: How the Rapper Grew From 'Dropout' to 'Yeezus'|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=June 14, 2013|accessdate=June 14, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617214400/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/1566931/kanye-west-how-the-rapper-grew-from-dropout-to-yeezus|archivedate=June 17, 2013}}</ref> On April 1, 2015, ''The College Dropout'' was certified triple [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), indicating three million copies moved.<ref>{{cite web|last=Suarez|first=Gary|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/garysuarez/2015/08/19/kanye-west-sales-platinum-gold/|title=Kanye West Is Having A Stellar Sales Year, Even Without A New Album|work=[[Forbes]]|date=August 19, 2015|accessdate=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619071335/http://www.forbes.com/sites/garysuarez/2015/08/19/kanye-west-sales-platinum-gold/|archive-date=June 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On the [[UK Albums Chart]], the album peaked at number 12, and the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) had certified it double platinum by November 25, 2004; this indicated shipments of 600,000 copies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/26133670/kanye-west-is-humbled-by-fans-as-his-debut-turns-ten|title=Kanye West is 'humbled' by fans as his debut turns ten|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=February 11, 2014|accessdate=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607233047/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/26133670/kanye-west-is-humbled-by-fans-as-his-debut-turns-ten|archive-date=June 7, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/kanye-west-brixton-academy-london-534451.html|title=Kanye West, Brixton Academy, London|work=The Independent|date=November 25, 2004|accessdate=September 23, 2019|author=Verma, Rahul }}</ref> As of 2018, ''The College Dropout'' is the fourteenth highest selling rap album in the UK in the 21st-century.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-uks-official-top-40-biggest-rap-albums-of-the-millennium-revealed__22808/ |title=The UK's Official Top 40 biggest rap albums of the Millennium revealed |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |date=May 4, 2018 |accessdate=July 10, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906012015/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-uks-official-top-40-biggest-rap-albums-of-the-millennium-revealed__22808/ |archivedate=September 6, 2018}}</ref> The album has sold over 4 million copies worldwide.<ref name=SMH>Columnist. [http://www.smh.com.au/news/music/mr-confidence-puts-it-all-on-the-line/2005/07/31/1122748516555.html Mr Confidence puts it all on the line] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022023807/http://www.smh.com.au/news/music/mr-confidence-puts-it-all-on-the-line/2005/07/31/1122748516555.html |date=October 22, 2013 }}. ''[[The Sun-Herald]]'' (August 1, 2005). Retrieved August 27, 2007.</ref>\n\nFour of the singles released in promotion of the album became top-20 chart [[Hit record|hits]]: \"Through the Wire\", \"Slow Jamz\", \"All Falls Down\" and \"Jesus Walks\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theboombox.com/kanye-west-the-college-dropout-test-of-time/|title=Does Kanye West's 'The College Dropout' Stand the Test of Time?|website=[[The Boombox]]|accessdate=October 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027232030/http://theboombox.com/kanye-west-the-college-dropout-test-of-time/|archive-date=October 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[The New Workout Plan]]\" was the fifth and last single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7504416/kanye-west-college-dropout-anniversary-new-workout-plan?firefox=1|title=Kanye West's \"The New Workout Plan\": Revisit His Hilariously Brilliant 'College Dropout' Single|website=Idolator|accessdate=October 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028033712/http://www.idolator.com/7504416/kanye-west-college-dropout-anniversary-new-workout-plan?firefox=1|archive-date=October 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Spaceship\" was planned to be the sixth single, but Def Jam decided to move on from ''The College Dropout''{{'}}s promotional campaign to begin marketing West's next album, ''[[Late Registration]]'' (2005).<ref>[http://www.rapbasement.com/kanye-west/050609-kanye-wests-lost-spaceship-video-still-shots-from-rapper-glc-view-them-all-here.html Kanye West's Lost \"Spaceship\" Video | Kanye West] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611041325/http://www.rapbasement.com/Kanye-West/050609-kanye-wests-lost-spaceship-video-still-shots-from-rapper-glc-view-them-all-here.html |date=June 11, 2009 }} Rap Basement Retrieved July 1, 2012</ref> At one point, \"Two Words\" was also intended to be released as a single, and a video for the song was filmed, and later uploaded by West online in 2009.<ref name=\"common\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1484512/kanye-west-plays-dropout-vips.jhtml |title=Common, John Mayer Drop in to Preview Kanye West's Dropout |date=January 21, 2004 |last=Reid |first=Shaheem |work=[[MTV]] |accessdate=June 17, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605062342/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1484512/kanye-west-plays-dropout-vips.jhtml |archivedate=June 5, 2011  }}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 87/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Kellman\">{{cite web|last=Kellman|first=Andy|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-college-dropout-mw0000326741|title=''The College Dropout'' \u2013 Kanye West|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=January 21, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603082238/http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-college-dropout-mw0000326741|archivedate=June 3, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pareles|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Pareles|url=http://blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=1942|title=Kanye West: ''The College Dropout''|journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|location=New York|issue=25|date=April 2004|accessdate=July 4, 2016|page=124|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050409000845/http://blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=1942|archivedate=April 9, 2005}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = A\u2212<ref name=\"Endelman\">{{cite journal|last=Endelman|first=Michael|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2004/02/13/college-dropout|title=''The College Dropout''|journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|location=New York|date=February 13, 2004|accessdate=July 23, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730013949/https://ew.com/article/2004/02/13/college-dropout/|archivedate=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=\"Baker\">{{cite news|last=Baker|first=Soren|authorlink=Soren Baker|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/feb/12/news/wk-popside12|title=You'll know his name|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 12, 2004|accessdate=July 23, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100913171817/http://articles.latimes.com/2004/feb/12/news/wk-popside12|archivedate=September 13, 2010}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{cite journal|title=Kanye West: ''The College Dropout''|journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|location=London|issue=126|date=May 2004|page=102}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 8.2/10<ref name=\"Mitchum\">{{cite web|last=Mitchum|first=Rob|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/8767-the-college-dropout/|title=Kanye West: ''The College Dropout''|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=February 20, 2004|accessdate=July 23, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731093001/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/8767-the-college-dropout/|archivedate=July 31, 2009}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Caramanica\">{{cite journal|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Caramanica|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/college-dropout-20040314|title=''The College Dropout''|work=Rolling Stone|location=New York|date=March 14, 2004|accessdate=December 26, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101220052935/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/college-dropout-20040314|archivedate=December 20, 2010}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev8Score = B+<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ryan|first=Chris|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JZ4ej5RmWFUC&pg=PA111&lpg=PA111|title=Kanye West: ''The College Dropout''|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|volume=19|issue=11|date=November 2003|accessdate=August 29, 2016|pages=111\u201312|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908013431/https://books.google.com/books?id=JZ4ej5RmWFUC&pg=PA111&lpg=PA111|archivedate=September 8, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Jones|first=Steve|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2004-02-09-listen-up_x.htm|title='Dropout': Well schooled|work=[[USA Today]]|location=McLean|date=February 9, 2004|accessdate=January 17, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221014439/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2004-02-09-listen-up_x.htm|archive-date=December 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = A<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2004-03-09/music/edges-of-the-groove/|title=Edges of the Groove|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|date=March 9, 2004|accessdate=August 5, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022202410/http://www.villagevoice.com/2004-03-09/music/edges-of-the-groove/|archivedate=October 22, 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n''The College Dropout'' was met with widespread critical acclaim. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from professional publications, the album received an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 87, based on 25 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/college-dropout/kanye-west|title=Reviews for ''College Dropout'' by Kanye West|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=December 26, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729050236/http://www.metacritic.com/music/college-dropout/kanye-west|archivedate=July 29, 2012}}</ref> \n\nThe record was hailed by Kelefa Sanneh from ''[[The New York Times]]'' as \"2004's first great hip-hop album\".<ref name=\"Sanneh\">{{cite news|last=Sanneh|first=Kelefa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/09/arts/music/09CHOI.html|title=No Reading And Writing, But Rapping Instead|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 9, 2004|accessdate=August 5, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114130405/http://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/09/arts/music/09CHOI.html|archivedate=November 14, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> Reviewing it for ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', [[Nathan Rabin]] observed in the music \"substance, social commentary, righteous anger, ornery humanism, dark humor, and even Christianity\", calling it \"one of those wonderful crossover albums that appeal to a huge audience without sacrificing a shred of integrity\".<ref name=\"Rabin\">{{cite web|last=Rabin|first=Nathan|authorlink=Nathan Rabin|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/kanye-west-the-college-dropout,11574/|title=Kanye West: The College Dropout|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=February 17, 2004|accessdate=December 26, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100126062327/http://www.avclub.com/articles/kanye-west-the-college-dropout%2C11574/|archivedate=January 26, 2010}}</ref> The staff of ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' said its exceptional hip hop production was miraculous during a time when hip hop's practice of sampling was becoming \"increasingly litigious\",<ref name=\"Mojo\"/> and those of ''[[URB (magazine)|URB]]'' deemed it \"both visceral and emotive, sprinkling the dancefloors with tears and sweat\".<ref name=\"URB\">{{cite journal|title=Kanye West, 'The College Dropout' (Roc-A-Fella/Def Jam)|journal=[[URB (magazine)|URB]]|location=Los Angeles|issue=114|date=March 12, 2004|page=111}}</ref> Dave Heaton from ''[[PopMatters]]'' found it \"musically engaging\" and \"a genuine extension of Kanye's personality and experiences\",<ref name=\"Heaton\"/> while Hua Hsu of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' felt that his sped-up samples \"carry a humble, human air\", allowing listeners to \"hear tiny traces of actual people inside\".<ref name=\"Hsu\">{{cite news|last=Hsu|first=Hua|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2004-02-10/music/the-benz-or-the-backpack/1|title=The Benz or the Backpack?|work=The Village Voice|location=New York|date=February 10, 2004|accessdate=July 23, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090707220649/http://www.villagevoice.com/2004-02-10/music/the-benz-or-the-backpack/1|archivedate=July 7, 2009}}</ref> Fellow ''Village Voice'' critic [[Robert Christgau]] wrote that \"not only does [West] create a unique role model, that role model is dangerous\u2014his arguments against education are as market-targeted as other rappers' arguments for thug life\".<ref name=\"Christgau\"/> In the opinion of ''[[Stylus Magazine]]''{{'}}s Josh Love, West \"subverts cliches from both sides of the hip-hop divide\" while \"trying to reflect the entire spectrum of hip-hop and black experience, looking for solace and salvation in the traditional safehouses of church and family\".<ref name=\"Love\"/> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s Michael Endelman elaborated on West's avoidance of the then-dominant \"gangsta\" persona of hip hop:\n\n{{cquote|West delivers the goods with a disarming mix of confessional honesty and sarcastic humor, earnest idealism and big-pimping materialism. In a scene still dominated by authenticity battles and gangsta posturing, he's a middle-class, politically conscious, post-thug, bourgeois rapper \u2013 and that's nothing to be ashamed of.<ref name=\"Endelman\"/>}}\n\nSome reviewers were more qualified in their praise. ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s [[Jon Caramanica]] felt that \"West isn't quite MC enough to hold down the entire disc\", though claimed that West's \"ace in the hole is his signature cozy sound\",<ref name=\"Caramanica\"/> while ''[[Slant Magazine]]''{{'}}s Sal Cinquemani observed \"too many guest artists, too many interludes, and just too many songs period\" on what he considered a \"chest-beatingly self-congratulatory\" yet humorous, deeply sincere, and affecting record.<ref name=\"Cinquemani\">{{cite web|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/kanye-west-the-college-dropout|title=Kanye West: ''The College Dropout''|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=March 14, 2004|accessdate=December 26, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150311215821/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/kanye-west-the-college-dropout|archivedate=March 11, 2015}}</ref> It was regarded by ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' critic Rob Mitchum as a \"flawed, overlong, hypocritical, egotistical, and altogether terrific album\".<ref name=\"Mitchum\"/> The staff of ''Rolling Stone'' were more receptive in a retrospective review than Caramanica was previously for the publication, calling the album \"a demonstration that hip-hop\u2014real, banging, commercial hip-hop\u2014could be a vehicle for nuanced self-examination and musical subtlety\".<ref name=\"RSguide\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/kanye-west/albumguide|title=Kanye West: Album Guide|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York|accessdate=August 5, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111205044352/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/kanye-west/albumguide|archivedate=December 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Rankings ===\n''The College Dropout'' was voted as the best album of the year by ''The Village Voice''{{'}}s [[Pazz & Jop]], an annual poll of American critics.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2005-10-18/specials/2004/|title=Pazz & Jop 2004|newspaper=The Village Voice|date=October 18, 2005|accessdate=July 31, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60b5fURGh?url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2005-10-18/specials/2004/|archivedate=July 31, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album elsewhere topped year-end lists by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=White|first=Julian|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/rolling.htm#2004|title=''Rolling Stone'' 2004 Critics|publisher=RocklistMusic.co.uk|accessdate=July 31, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60b5wHd0y?url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/rolling.htm|archivedate=July 31, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fyLttHWpa9EC&pg=PA68|title=40 Best Albums of the Year: 1) ''The College Dropout''|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|page=68|accessdate=January 21, 2005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415013147/http://books.google.com/books?id=fyLttHWpa9EC&pg=PA68|archivedate=April 15, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7iYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA50|title=Vibe Magazine \u2013 January 2005|website=Vibe|volume=13|issue=1|date=January 2005|accessdate=March 27, 2020|page=50}}</ref> and ''[[PopMatters]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/music/best2004/index-5-1.shtml|title=Top 100 Albums of 2004|website=PopMatters|accessdate=August 11, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050112132155/http://www.popmatters.com/music/best2004/index-5-1.shtml|archivedate=January 7, 2005}}</ref> Dutch magazine ''[[OOR]]'' named it the seventh best album of 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muzieklijstjes.nl/2004.htm|title=Jaarlijst Oor 2004|publisher=Muzieklijstjes|accessdate=August 11, 2019|language=Dutch|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603134514/http://www.muzieklijstjes.nl/2004.htm|archivedate=June 3, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' named ''The College Dropout'' the second best album of 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/bb/yearend/2004/top10.jsp|title=Billboard 2004 \u2013 The Year in Music|website=Billboard|accessdate=August 11, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050203204041/https://www.billboard.com/bb/yearend/2004/top10.jsp|archivedate=February 3, 2005}}</ref> [[Napster (streaming music service)|Rhapsody]] named it the seventh best album of the decade and the fourth best hip hop album of the decade.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rhapsody Editorial|url=http://blog.rhapsody.com/2009/12/100-best-pop-albums-of-the-decade-10-1.html|title=Rhapsody's 100 Best Albums of the Decade|publisher=[[Napster (streaming music service)|Rhapsody]]|date=December 4, 2009|accessdate=January 21, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60b2HhznW?url=http://blog.rhapsody.com/2009/12/100-best-pop-albums-of-the-decade-10-1.html|archivedate=July 31, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Chennault|first=Sam|url=http://blog.rhapsody.com/2009/10/hiphopdecade.html|title=Hip-Hop's Best Albums of the Decade|publisher=Rhapsody|date=October 31, 2009|accessdate=June 17, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60b45O02x?url=http://blog.rhapsody.com/2009/10/hiphopdecade.html|archivedate=July 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, ''Pitchfork'' named it No. 50 in their best albums of 2000\u20132004.<ref>{{cite web|author=''Pitchfork'' staff|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5956-the-top-100-albums-of-2000-04-part-one/6/|title=The Top 100 Albums of 2000\u201304|work=Pitchfork|date=February 7, 2005|accessdate=July 31, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100409001047/http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5956-the-top-100-albums-of-2000-04-part-one/6/|archivedate=April 9, 2010}}</ref> In 2006, the album was named by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' as one of the 100 best albums of all time.<ref name=\"time.com\">{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2006/11/02/the-all-time-100-albums/slide/the-college-dropout/|title=''Time'' 100 Best Albums of All Time|work=Time|date=November 2, 2006|accessdate=May 25, 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111021211602/http://entertainment.time.com/2006/11/02/the-all-time-100-albums/slide/the-college-dropout/|archivedate=October 21, 2011}}</ref> In its retrospective 2007 issue, ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' named it one of the magazine's \"XXL\"-rated releases; this perfect rating had previously been given by the magazine to only sixteen other albums.<ref name = \"XXL\">{{cite journal|author=XXL|authorlink=XXL (magazine)|journal=XXL|title=Retrospective: XXL Albums|date=December 2007|pages=}}</ref> In 2012, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' named the album one of the classic albums of the last decade,<ref>{{cite web|last=Drake|first=David|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/12/25-rap-albums-from-the-past-decade-that-deserve-classic-status/kanye-west-college-dropout|title=25 Rap Albums From the Past Decade That Deserve Classic Status: Kanye West, The College Dropout (2004)|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=December 6, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209013557/http://www.complex.com/music/2012/12/25-rap-albums-from-the-past-decade-that-deserve-classic-status/kanye-west-college-dropout|archivedate=December 9, 2012}}</ref> and the 20th best hip hop debut album ever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/11/the-50-greatest-debut-albums-in-hip-hop-history/kanye-west-the-college-dropout|title=The 50 Greatest Debut Albums in Hip-Hop History: 20. Kanye West, The College Dropout|work=Complex|accessdate=November 27, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102073636/http://www.complex.com/music/2012/11/the-50-greatest-debut-albums-in-hip-hop-history/kanye-west-the-college-dropout|archivedate=January 2, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Dagsavisen]]'' listed the album eleventh in its list of the top forty albums of the 2000s decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dagsavisen.no/kultur/article452521.ece|title=Top 40 Albums of the 2000s|website=Dagsavisen|date=November 24, 2009|accessdate=August 5, 2019|language=Danish|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305042740/http://www.dagsavisen.no/kultur/article452521.ece|archivedate=March 5, 2010}}</ref> The album was also included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dimery|first1=Robert|last2=Lydon|first2=Michael|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|publisher=Universe|isbn=0-7893-1371-5|date=February 7, 2006|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Country\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n! Reference\n|-\n| ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rowspan=\"18\"| United States\n| The 50 Best Albums of the 2000s\n| 2009\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/the-best-music-of-the-decade-1798221680|title=Top 50 Albums of the 2000s|website=The A.V. Club|date=November 19, 2009|accessdate=August 5, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804134804/https://music.avclub.com/the-best-music-of-the-decade-1798221680|archivedate=August 4, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[BET]]\n| The Best Albums of the 2000s\n| 2009\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3 \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bet.com/Music/photos/msc_bestalbumsofthedecade_12.24.09.htm?i=2|title=Best Albums of 2000s|publisher=BET|accessdate=August 5, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091229103859/http://www.bet.com/Music/photos/msc_bestalbumsofthedecade_12.24.09.htm?i=2|archivedate=December 29, 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| The Top 100 Albums of the 2000s \n| 2009\n| styl